1933 Chevy Roadster, All steel body,  429 Cu in.(7.03 L) Cadillac Engine, 340 HP. 480 lb torque.  GM 400 Transmission,  Ford 9 inch rear end.  This is how the 50's Hot Rods were built.  Other than the Dual Brake master Cylinder and the 6-way Electric seat this is a Vintage style Hot Rod. It's not what today is called a Rat Rod, nothing Ratty about this one.  Chevy bodies of this vintage had a wood structure that the tin was then fastened to it by nails. All wood has been replaced with steel, along with the floor boards.  The whole underbody and floor boards have been covered with bed liner. This is not a Bondo Bucket.  The reason I'm selling it is that age is creeping up on me and it's time to thin out the herd. I have more toys than I can drive. It's time for someone else to have fun. I'm asking $20,000 that's a fraction of what it would cost to build chool Hot Rodanother one like it. If you don't have the money, please don't waste my time, the price is firm.  I have sold cars to overseas buyers in the past and can help arrange shipping.

Up for sale is this early 70's Opel GT  with only 37,160 original miles for $8200. I have always stored it inside my heated garage with a car cover on it, and the previous owner did the same.  It has 1.9 liter inline 4 cylinder and a 4 speed syncro-mesh manual gearbox and  disc brakes up front and rack and pinion steering.  This car was built in West Germany by the Opel company.  General Motors contracted Opel to build them and they were sold at a Pontiac dealership.  They are often referred to as the "mini corvette", even though they were designed first.  It has the pop up headlights that rotate instead of hinge vertically. The interior is in great shape too.  All dials and gauges work properly and the upholstery has no tears or rips in it.  The drivers side floor mat does have a worn spot from the drivers heel.   It has lap and shoulder belts that were added when they were received in the US.  So the buckles have the GM badge on them. It has a "parcel shelf" behind the front seats where you can put groceries or golf clubs.  It is a fastback, so there is no trunk.  The spare tire is behind a flap below the rear window.   The previous owner had some work done on the head and installed a slightly better exhaust header while he was at it. It is a great cruising car that is actually comfortable and a joy to drive.  It by no means is "fast" or "quick", despite its looks.  So if your looking for something that will do burnouts, this is not it.  I purchased this car about 8 years ago for my son and I to drive.  He learned to drive a "stick shift" at the age of 12 and was able to take it to his prom.  He has recently left the house and so I wont be using it as much, which is why I am selling it.  It does have one spot of rust on the drivers side that was there when I got it.  I have included a photo of that spot.  I have made sure to dry the car real good every time I washed it.    Since I have owned it I have had the following done by and older mechanic; Changed the oil and filter  New front and rear shocks Alignment A few gaskets, seals and bearings  Its all original except for the following upgrades: Wheels Carb and K@N air filter (carb is a weber and I have the original Solex) Electronic ignition Fuel Pump Fuel/Water separator New battery last year Exhaust header  It will come with: Owners manual Two service manuals, (one has the disc with manual on it), these are complete shop manuals Owners workshop manual Opel parts catalogue Opel GT source parts catalogue Original Solex carb Bag of Misc. goodies  Thanks for looking I don't need help selling, Cash only, and not interested in any trades including guns or other cars  Peter  AK area code-830-1668 Text and calls ok

Buy one ford ranger, get the 2nd one free!  I am selling TWO ford ranger 4wd trucks AS A SET FOR ONE PRICE. Sorry, I will not part out. Parts are interchangeable between both of them. All the spares you could need.  Both are automatics and 4WD models.  Both are the supercab version with 4 doors.  Both have average interiors and the typical ford seat rub issue. They are not perfect on the inside, but dont have smells either.  Both have alaska windshields.  Both have decent tires.  Both run and drive, but each has its own issues.  One is tagged, the other is not.  One has a title, the other does not.  One is a 2000 model, the other is a 2001 model.  One has running boards, the other does not.  One has 230,000 miles, the other has 161,000 miles.  One has privacy glass on the door windows, the other does not.  The Other stuff:  The overdrive indicator light is flashing on the 2001. Dont have a code reader that will read it..could be a simple fix.  The 2000 will either need the 4wd selector switch fixed or the 4wd looked at.  The 2000 has new rotors, brakes, and brake calipers.  The tailgate latch just broke on the 2000..just releases one side, so you will need a screwdriver to unlatch the other side or leave it unlatched.   Use one for all the spare parts you will ever need or fix both and have 2 rigs to drive.  I have owned these trucks for a few years. I used the tagged one during summers to haul parts/materials back from lowes and whatnot. I bought the other at an auto auction as a spare parts rig for the tagged one, changed my mind, and then fixed it up. It had minor damage to the front passenger corner, so it doesnt take much for an insurance company to total out these older rigs. Their loss, my gain at the time.   Pic shows plastic fender missing on the 2001, but it is inside the cab.  The lower valence for the 2000 is in the truck bed and included. I took it off as I was going to put a small plow on the truck and then changed my mind.  Im selling because I have too many vehicles.  I have other vehicles i am selling at various prices with other issues I have kept for  various reasons over the years. I now have 9 vehicles and all but one runs and drives. Simply dont have the time or inclinqtion to do all the little things to sell them for more. My loss your gain.  $3500 FIRM. I have an F150 i need to fix, and gotta pay bills.
